The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is well-equipped and the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as well as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics to lower prices.
Perhaps it will not be allowed to wait any longer.
The fact that the Czech mobile phone providers are working at the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on mobile.cz.
This also confirmed the ČTù Telecommunications Authority, which pointed out that the price for a SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradox situation - for some Czech mobile customers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a struggle.
Maybe it sounds paradox, but in Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile operators would like to boast that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with a network of its own has no more than many chances (otherwise he would probably not even find any frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
In particular, the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market brought a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile providers had to respond to.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices on the market in the United Kingdom as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
Besides, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February, we reported on the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus raise to the country's fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually defined as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone conversations and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least half cheaper SMS than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to set an unclievable target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"A real guy chooses Mobilking - the provider they like and who they can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could occur in Poland as well as in the Czech Republic.
It also doubts the press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepýk: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively narrowed from the point of view of the service offer."
In Czech Republic, no chance, the mobile phone providers
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look forward to it.
It will come rather to a market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says Jana Studničková, press speaker of the Penta Finance Group.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile phone providers in the Czech Republic are not only attracted to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Its interest at the start of a virtual mobile phone provider has long been shown by the group GTS Novera, who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the business sector.
"We have a great interest in offering not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in the negotiations," said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times come now.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this point, we do not assume that there is a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň, in his statement for Mobil.cz from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificities of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds, in rare accordance with the statement of O2: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobile, a virtual provider will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point, we had to have a concrete offer to be able to think in such a short time."
Vodafone focuses on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepýký says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we see from the customer's perspective as the best.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a fall in profits.
So why should it be made easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
That suppliers can draw on a string when it comes to something, it also lays down the long slope and everything about the origin of U:fon.
Perhaps the strongest pressure towards ČTù went the time when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also the public information available from the ČTÚ website.
Now, however, you just need to use U:fon as an argument, why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile radio market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTù, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
It has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
But this related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract between a mobile provider and a virtual provider has come to a conclusion on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classic suppliers," according to our inquiry Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
The representatives of the suppliers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
From an authority that represents consumer interests and should, among other things, take into account that no one abuses its position on the market, this is more than worrying.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual providers work quite normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, it is likely that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction do not belong to the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is really shocking that the almost already rotating connection of the three mobile phone providers is derived from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just an accident is at hand.
Just as the absolute same fuel price in the tankers is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a hard competition struggle.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs in this case which have been the object of anti-competitive actions, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way on the matter.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so neither does it have the corresponding increased responsibility for its operations on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening the mobile phone market for virtual providers are probably also lacking by the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTÚ, which, from the point of view of economic competition, is a single market.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile phone provider has, logically, the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily assumes a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting similarly.
In so doing, there are a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Novera) who complain that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The deceleration of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services that distances the ÚOHS from the whole issue.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to implement the recently adopted telecommunications law's novelty to extend the ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this only too well, but they probably have different interests.
It's all right if no one's looking.
The operation of any pseudovirtual providers, of which there are also several in the Czech mobile networks, is not observed.
There are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but only part of them are public.
This is usually the case for companies operating in the multilevel marketing sector.
For example, mobile telephone services offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only selected.
The funny thing is that the company appears to be a classic company, which orders a lot of SIM cards.
As an important customer it will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar similar type of sale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be an infringement of the contractual conditions with which we will then be involved, which can lead to the termination of cooperation with the company concerned," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not happen to mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an action.
The activities of these companies do not cause them to lose their profits, while at the same time, unlike actual virtual suppliers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepýky notes on possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a very low percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card does not run on their behalf in their phone, so they cannot have full access to it as normal customers of mobile phones."
However, the ČTù had to at least appear strange.
There is also another question for the UOHS.
Do mobile phone providers close their eyes before such a procedure, why do they block against a virtual provider?
It is added that the UOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to be satisfied with the supplier's statement, they knew nothing about it and their business conditions would prohibit it.
When Czech is no longer the most expensive
As already stressed in the text several times, the market entry of virtual providers brought a significant drop in prices for the various services.
In this way virtually all countries where virtual providers have been created have tried to prevent their origin from virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a too small, or too highly-intended market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
However, in the highly developed countries, the regulatory bodies are currently taking action, which are not in any way interested in mobile phones, but are trying to be true to their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they reached that the first virtual operator was created, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
In the light of our experience, we cannot escape the impression that uncertainty in the skills in these cases is more than beneficial.
But we don't throw the flint into the oven.
If the background information agrees and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile phone market may be moving again soon.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the UOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other stakeholders (to discriminate).
And then the Czechs will finally no longer call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
