Hepatitis: When is the doctor to be contacted?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated to be hundreds of thousands in this country, however, only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the total term for liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common; however, the symptoms differ from one another and the diseases.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two different species: in hepatitis A and E through the digestion tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, skeletal secretion or mirror).
Travellers are recommended for vaccination against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two to three weeks after contamination of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and fractures.
Then the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine is dark, and the healing can last up to two or three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die of hepatitis B-dissolved diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis each year.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every 10 infected are in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have severe consequences: it may lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancers untreated.
Most infected people do not even know about their illness, since the errant has accidentally destroyed the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms are shown after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely precautions such as regular checks are essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already evidenced in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor in the first signs of unknown origin.
In due course, the disease is healthy, the virus can be eradicated, thus preventing the risk of infection and predisposing cancer.
The World Day of Hepatitis is held on September 30th, 2004 for the first time in patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of these chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early recognition.
